This quest is the second of three projects we’re working on for this campaign - an ERC20 token project! In the previous quest, we learnt how to deploy a simple smart contract onto the Avalanche Fuji Testnet. 
This quest, we’ll be picking up more advanced Solidity skills, learning about the Hardhat development framework, and deploying our ERC20 token onto a local Subnet!

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to Core
Core is a non-custodial browser extension engineered for users to seamlessly and securely use Web3 powered by Avalanche. It is an all-in-one operating system bringing together Avalanche apps, Subnets, bridges, and NFTs in one seamless, high-performance browser experience. 
Besides providing holistic support for all things Avalanche, Core connects to other networks as well (Ethereum, Bitcoin, other EVM-based networks) so it can truly be your one-stop-shop for everything crypto!

As of its release, Core is the easiest way to access the full power of Web3 on Avalanche. Core users will find that often cumbersome functions, like adding new tokens to your portfolio, are now automated. Above all, Core is designed to be simple, secure, practical, and convenient. Core is optimized to minimize the number of clicks needed to complete an action. 

Core offers nine primary features, with more coming in future releases. The primary features released thus far include:
  1. Bridge — bridge native Bitcoin using the same trusted technology powering the Avalanche Bridge (support for Ethereum tokens (ERC-20) is coming soon)
  2. Swap — swap hundreds of Avalanche tokens directly from Core (powered by ParaSwap)
  3. Buy — fund Core with cash in just a few clicks (powered by MoonPay)
  4. Ledger-enabled — compatible with industry-leading, secure hardware wallet
  5. Portfolio — view all assets in a unified display without having to manually add token addresses or switch networks
  6. Collectibles Gallery — manage and display all of your NFTs in one consolidated portal
  7. Subnets — Native support for subnets including DFK and Swimmer with dynamic support forthcoming
  8. Address Book — create contacts to save frequently used, trusted addresses
  9. Account Switcher — create and manage multiple addresses using the same recovery phrase
Step 2: Setting Up a Wallet in Core
Now, let’s create our wallet in Core. As it currently only supports the Google Chrome browser, please download Google Chrome before proceeding with the remainder of this step.
Open your Google Chrome browser and continue with the rest of these steps:
  1. Head to the Core site and click on ‘Core Extension’ on the bottom left corner of the screen
  2. You’ll be redirected to the chrome web store, add the core extension to chrome by clicking on ‘Add to Chrome’
  3. After adding the extension to chrome, you’ll be redirected to the Core page. Click on ‘Create a New Wallet’
  4. Enter the necessary fields with information of your choice. Check the two acknowledgement boxes and click on ‘Save’
  5. In the next page, the secret recovery phrase will show up. Copy the secret recovery phrase and store it in a secure location. This key is used to import your existing wallet so if the key phrase is lost, you will not be able to recover your wallet anymore. Check the acknowledge box and click on ‘Next’
  6. Verify your Secret recovery phrase on the next page and click ‘Next’
  7. Follow the instructions prompted to pin the Core extension for easier access later on.
  8. And we’re done! Once you reach this step, you should get an output similar to that of the image in ‘Expected output’

Step 3: Hardhat Development Framework
Hardhat is a development environment that helps developers in testing, compiling, deploying and debugging decentralized applications on the Ethereum blockchain. The Hardhat smart contract development environment provides tools for developers to manage their development workflow. It also provides automation in specific steps alongside the facility of new and productive functions.  
Hardhat has a pre-built local Ethereum network tailored for development. Hardhat also features the facility of stack traces and messages in the event of decentralised application failure which provides the tools to identify the instance and the cause of the failure. 

Another feature of Hardhat is that it provides a diverse range of utility plugins. In conclusion, Hardhat is a development framework that provides various tools that helps developers in all stages of the decentralised application lifecycle. 

As learning about the entirety of Hardhat is outside the scope of this campaign, we won't be covering in detail all that Hardhat has to offer. But instead, we’ll focus on how we can use Hardhat to achieve our goal in this quest - which is to deploy our smart contract (SC) to a local Subnet. If you want to learn more about Hardhat, you can refer to our Hardhat for Web3 Development Learn module.
Step 4: Introduction to Token Standards
Before we proceed, let’s touch a bit on the concept of token standards. As we know by now, SCs are scripts containing rules that exist on a blockchain. SC standards refer to a set of rules that a SC must comply with in order to function properly on the blockchain that it exists on.
With this predefined set of SC rules and defined parameters, there is a guideline or rulebook that allows anyone with a bit of coding knowledge to create their own blockchain-complaint SC. 

Thus brings us to token standards, which is a subset of SC standards. For SC compatible blockchains, token standards represent a guide for the issuance, creation, and deployment of new tokens on the underlying blockchain.

Ethereum Request for Comment (ERC) is essentially a set of technical documents containing guidelines on developing a SC. They define a specific set of functions for each token type and facilitate the interaction between applications and SCs. Some of the more common token standards include ERC-20, ERC-721, ERC-777, and ERC-1155. 

If you’re interested, you can read more about token standards here.
Step 5: ERC20 Token Standard
ERC20 is a token standard used within the Ethereum blockchain. As mentioned in the step earlier, it dictates the rules and actions that an Ethereum token or SC must follow and the instructions to implement them.  
Compliant tokens following ERC20 would need to implement the following functions.
  • totalSupply(): provides information about the total token supply
  • balanceOf(): provides account balance of the owner's account
  • transfer(): executes transfers of a specified number of tokens to a specified address
  • transferFrom(): executes transfers of a specified number of tokens from a specified address
  • approve(): allow a spender to withdraw a set number of tokens from a specified account
  • allowance(): returns a set number of tokens from a spender to the owner
 
These functions would also trigger up to 2 events - these are the transfer event that is triggered when there is a movement of tokens from party to another, and the approval/validation event which is activated whenever approval is needed 

Now that we have gone through what the ERC20 standard is, in the next step we will go through how to create a ERC20 smart contract.
Step 6: Understanding the ERC20 Token SC
As ERC20 has widespread adoption, it is not hard to find templates of SCs that follow the ERC20 token standard. One example of where we can find such a template is from OpenZeppelin. 
OpenZeppelin is an open-source framework to build secure SCs. Among its other features, one of the reasons why it is used very commonly among developers is its rich repository of open-source SCs that one can refer to.

OpenZeppelin also has a token SC generator, which is what we’ll be using for this quest. Now, let’s head to the site to proceed. This site provides a Graphical User Interface (GUI) that we can use to add Solidity code to our SC.



First, we’ll need to ensure that ‘ERC20’ is selected, which should be the default option. If you look at the SC now, you might be wondering why it looks so sparse. Well, that is because this SC is currently using a Solidity feature called import. 

If you click on @openzeppelin/contracts/token/ERC20/ERC20.sol inside the SC, you’ll be redirected to another page. This page contains the code to a template ERC20 SC. If you scroll down to view the SC, you’ll see that it includes the functions mentioned earlier like the totalSupply() (line 94) , balanceOf (line 101), transfer (line 113) and so on.

Remember earlier in this step we mentioned that OpenZeppelin contains an exhaustive repository of SCs? Well this is one of such SCs. If you were to explore the OpenZeppelin repository, you’ll find that there are many more of such SCs.

With just a simple import line and stating that your SC is ERC20, your SC is able to inherit all the properties of the SC that you’ve imported. Awesome!
Step 7: Editing the ERC20 Token SC
As mentioned in the step above, a cool feature about this SC generator is that it allows us to add features to our SC by using a GUI, the GUI then adds the corresponding Solidity code for the selected features into our SC.
The first feature we’ll be adding is Mintable, which allows only privileged accounts to be able to create more supply. To add the Mintable feature into our SC, we can check the box beside ‘Mintable’ under the ‘FEATURES’ tab on the left of the screen. After doing so, you’ll see that there are a few new changes to your SC.
  1. A new SC has been imported
  2. A new property of Ownable has been inherited by your SC
  3. A new function mint() has been added that allows only the owner to mint tokens

The second feature we’ll be adding is Burnable, which allows users to destroy their tokens. Again, add the Burnable feature by checking the box beside ‘Burnable’ under the ‘FEATURES’ tab. Two new changes will be made to our SC.
  1. A new SC has been imported
  2. A new property of ERC20Burnable has been inherited

Just like that, our SC has been customized by quite a bit! Now let’s move on to configuring our local set up to prepare for the deployment of our SC.

Step 11: (Gitpod) Exposing Port
This step is only relevant for learners who are using Gitpod. If you’re doing this quest locally on your machine, please skip this step and proceed to the next step. For learners who are using Gitpod, we’ll need to do one additional step here before proceeding. Since we’re using a Linux cloud instance hosted on Gitpod, we’ll need a way for our local machine to communicate with the cloud instance - we’ll do this by exposing a port on Gitpod.
Remember the RPC URL you copied earlier? This is its format:
  • http://127.0.0.1:{port_number}/ext/bc/blockchain_ID/rpc

Take note of the port number, since this is the port we’ll be exposing. You’ll need to switch to the ‘PORTS’ tab, which is beside the ‘TERMINAL’ tab at the bottom of your Gitpod page. 

Once there, find the row with the port number identified earlier and right click on the port number. Then, select the ‘Make Public’ option. After doing so, you’ll notice that the ‘State’ has been changed to ‘open (public)’. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ if you require a reference.

Then, copy the address beside that port number. This will be the URL that we’ll be using to interact with our Subnet in the next few steps. But before we do that, we’ll need to construct our new RPC URL, the format should be as follows. The blockchain_ID can be taken from the old RPC URL.
  • {public_URL}/ext/bc/blockchain_ID/rpc

For example, if your original RPC URL was this:
  • http://127.0.0.1:9652/ext/bc/2HAtqoJ6qPzSVpuTNHrmH5pTsmSt4SvQLByrBTtHBL5noJDKx2/rpc
Your new RPC URL to use is:
  • https://9652-stackupdev-advancingint-vyd9ahq871m.ws-us77.gitpod.io/ext/bc/2HAtqoJ6qPzSVpuTNHrmH5pTsmSt4SvQLByrBTtHBL5noJDKx2/rpc

Now that we have our RPC URL, we can proceed with the next steps! Note that for all subsequent steps, whenever you’re using an RPC URL, you should be using this new URL.

Troubleshooting: If you have trouble making your Gitpod port public, try running this command in your Gitpod terminal gp ports visibility 3000:public, but replace 3000 with your port number. We’ve noticed that sometimes Gitpod’s port state doesn’t refresh to public despite it already changing in the background. As such, try to proceed with the subsequent steps even though the state still shows private. However, if you run into an error in Step 15 when deploying your smart contract, then you might need to refresh your Gitpod workspace session and start from Step 8 again.

Step 13: Preparing the Hardhat Configuration File
Now that you have cloned the project, let’s go through the file structure of the project to get a high level understanding of the contents in the project directory. The important files are NewTestToken.sol and the hardhat.config.ts. The first one is our ERC20 SC and the latter refers to our Hardhat configuration file.
So now we’ll need to configure the Hardhat framework to specify to Hardhat that we intend for our project to interact with our local Subnet, the one we just deployed. We need to specify this because the default connects us to the Hardhat Network instead. Open hardhat.config.ts using your code editor.

If you’ve not used Hardhat before, this file might seem very foreign to you. Read on to learn more about Hardhat and how the two files work. You probably will find it easier to understand.

As mentioned earlier, Hardhat is a development framework, so you can think of it as the skeleton of your project. Following the same analogy, the configuration file, aka hardhat.config.ts, can be thought of as the brains of your project. Here you can adjust the configurations (hence the name) of your project, such as what libraries you wish to import, what version of Solidity you want to use etc. Essentially, you’re choosing what settings you wish to configure for your project.

One of these settings is network. One of the features of Hardhat is that it allows you to conveniently choose between different networks that you wish to interact with. If you look at lines 72 to 96 of hardhat.config.ts, you can see that there are 4 networks configured here: hardhat, local, fuji and mainnet. Each of these have their own configurations: url, chainId etc.

What we’ll need to do now is to replace the value of url and accounts with the RPC URL and private key respectively that we got in our terminal from earlier on. Note: for learners using Gitpod, the RPC URL you’ll be using is the one you got from Step 11.

In line 79 and 82, you will need to replace the placeholder values with the RPC URL and the private key of the account that was credited with the airdrop during the deployment of the Subnet in the earlier steps. Remember to save your script after you’re done editing the fields. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference if you are unsure of what fields to change.

Troubleshooting: If you encounter this error HH101: Hardhat was set to use chain id 777, but connected to a chain with id 1234, run the following commands in the terminal you used to run your AvalancheCli commands:

Step 16: Interacting with the SC Using Hardhat
How to start
Another one of Hardhat’s features is its console - with the console, you are able to interact with SCs by inserting lines of code into the console and seeing the result in real time, all without needing to write an entire script. However, similar to writing scripts, the code entered in the console must be in either Javascript or Typescript.
To enter the console, you will need to type the following command in your terminal. After doing so, your terminal will look like the image in ‘How to start’. Note: even if you used Gitpod, you should be typing the commands below in your local machine’s terminal.

yarn console --network local

From here you can add your code to the console and it will run accordingly. For this step, we’ll be querying the token name, decimals and the balance of the address that holds the minted tokens. We will also go through how you can mint more tokens by interacting with the deployed SC.

Let’s start! Replace Add_your_Contract_Address_here in the code below with the address of your deployed contract (this is the address in the output of your terminal in the previous step). Once you’ve done so, paste the three lines of code into your terminal (the one you’re using for the Hardhat console).

const Coin = await ethers.getContractFactory('NewTestToken'); const coin = await Coin.attach('Add_your_Contract_Address_here'); let accounts = await ethers.provider.listAccounts();

Don’t worry if you get an undefined response for each line of code; this is expected since there is no output in any of the above code, we’re only assigning values to variables. Now let’s go through how we can interact with our deployed SC.

To get the name of your token, you will need to run the command below. This will return the name of your ERC20 token. Since we configured our token name in the earlier steps, it should be your StackUp username.

await coin.name()

Now run the code below, this will return you with the number of decimals your token has. Note that the blockchain does not store decimal places, only whole numbers. Hence the decimal field is needed to capture this information. After running the command, you should be returned with 18 - this indicates that your token has 18 decimal places.

await coin.decimals()

Now let’s try getting the balance of the wallet address that contains our minted tokens. We can run the command below to do so. The result that you should get is 123456789000000000000000000. If you were to divide that number by 1018, you will get 123456789 which is the number of tokens that were originally minted.

(await coin.balanceOf(accounts[0])).toString()

So now that you are able to do basic queries, let’s move on to something more advanced! Let’s try interacting with a function we specified within our deployed SC. In particular, let’s try calling the mint() function of our SC to mint some tokens!

For this we will be minting just 2 to a wallet. This translates to 0.0000000000000000002 of a token as there are 18 decimal places. We can call the mint() function by running the code below. After doing so, your terminal should output something similar to the image in ‘Expected output’.

await coin.mint(accounts[0],2)

To check if the minting worked, let’s run the balanceOf code that we ran earlier. Tip: you can use the up arrow on your keyboard to quickly toggle to the previous commands entered. You’ll see that the amount now becomes 123456789000000000000000002, showing that we have indeed minted 2 new tokens!
Expected output
